Ambiguity & The Zaz Narrative

Matthew Belloni: Eriq, you=E2=80=99ve read the complaint and the contract a=
nd the all-important =E2=80=9Cmatching rights=E2=80=9D section, which Warne=
r Discovery says allows it to =E2=80=9Cmatch=E2=80=9D Amazon=E2=80=99s $1.8=
 billion offer for the =E2=80=9CC=E2=80=9D package of games. What do you ma=
ke of Warners=E2=80=99 claims and the NBA=E2=80=99s potential defense?

Eriq Gardner: It strikes me that Warners is navigating this situation rathe=
r cautiously. Yes, I know Zaz hired Edelman, and Charles Barkley has said h=
is piece. But the language of the complaint is notably restrained, at least=
 in terms of these court papers. We don=E2=80=99t see any nuclear buttons p=
ressed=E2=80=94no hot rhetoric in the opening, no NFL Sunday Ticket-type an=
titrust claim, no naming of Amazon as a co-defendant. Going that far would =
likely really provoke the league. Instead, this suit is a pretty
straightforward contract case, presenting an interpretation of what exactly=
 Warners has the right to match=E2=80=94an interpretation, of course, that =
will now be contested.

People love to dunk on Zaslav (sorry for the hoops pun), but I don=E2=80=99=
t think Warners=E2=80=99 view of the contract is outlandish. The company cu=
rrently enjoys cable rights, which under the old deal includes the ability =
to transmit games onto cable networks when they=E2=80=99re being streamed. =
There=E2=80=99s also the point that many Amazon Prime customers will watch =
these games on a television. From the perspective of many fans, watching TB=
S or Prime Video is basically the same=E2=80=94you just fire up the Roku an=
d click on the app. That said, I=E2=80=99m unconvinced the contract languag=
e unambiguously states that Warner gets to match Amazon. That=E2=80=99s a c=
rucial point, because if the judge doesn=E2=80=99t find that the contract l=
anguage is clear, the parties will likely have to engage in extensive fact-=
finding and
discussions around the original intent behind the =E2=80=9Cmatching rights=
=E2=80=9D clause.

I think what Warners really needs from this court is an injunction, which i=
s why the lawyers are trying their best to present a winning case based pur=
ely on contract language. But an early decision that allows Turner to keep =
broadcasting games will be hard to obtain=E2=80=94not only due to the possi=
bly ambiguous nature of the contract, but also because Warners must demonst=
rate irreparable harm to its business absent an injunction, which the compl=
aint struggles to demonstrate. It notes that =E2=80=9CNBA telecast rights p=
rovide halo benefits,=E2=80=9D such as promotional opportunities, but I dou=
bt that=E2=80=99s enough. It=E2=80=99s possible the lawyers stopped short o=
f describing life after the NBA because Zaz was wary of further impacting t=
he company=E2=80=99s stock price.

The complaint alleges that the NBA structured the Amazon deal differently f=
or the =E2=80=9Csole purpose of attempting to thwart TBS=E2=80=99s
matching rights=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94essentially that the league never wanted t=
o re-up with TNT. But so what? If the contract allows alternatives, why can=
=E2=80=99t the league pursue them?

Eriq: My first inclination is to criticize Zaz for complaining about being =
outmaneuvered=E2=80=A6 but in fairness, there=E2=80=99s a specific line in =
the contract stating that neither party should act primarily to circumvent =
matching rights when it comes to offers from other entities. Thus, if Adam =
Silver is hypothetically encouraging Amazon C.E.O. Andy Jassy to pledge bil=
lions of dollars in an up-front payment, knowing that Zaz can=E2=80=99t mat=
ch, that could qualify as a breach of contract. Essentially, it=E2=80=99s a=
 way of claiming the NBA is not acting as an honest broker.

Bill, I find this narrative of Zaslav as the defender of content in the fac=
e of a tech takeover to be pretty disingenuous. Zaz would sell his company =
to Amazon (or Apple=E2=80=A6 or Alphabet=E2=80=A6) in a heartbeat if a) the=
y
were interested, and b) the government would allow it. Isn=E2=80=99t this a=
ll just posturing to loosen regulations so Zaslav can merge or sell?

Bill Cohan: Obviously, every public company is for sale, regardless of what=
 anyone says at any time. At the right price, at the right time, things get=
 sold. So, yes, if Amazon or Apple came along and wanted to buy WBD, for a =
=E2=80=9Cfair=E2=80=9D price, Zaz and his two big shareholders, John Malone=
 and Steven Newhouse, would sell. But we both know that is unlikely, especi=
ally in the near term.

So what=E2=80=99s Zaz to do until he gets the call from Tim Cook? He has to=
 do what he thinks is right for the WBD stakeholders, as unpopular as some =
of those things may be both internally and externally. He made no friends b=
y killing off Batgirl after the film was finished, or by continuing to cut =
headcount at CNN and elsewhere. Zaz cosplaying as the defender of Hollywood=
 versus the Tech Invaders seems, to
me, like a legit role for him, or for Bob Iger at Disney or Brian Roberts a=
t Comcast. But Iger is still licking his wounds from his last round with Ne=
lson Peltz, and Brian has never been a firebrand, preferring to do his spea=
king through his actions, not his words. So that pretty much leaves Zaz to =
make the case.

Is he the best messenger? Probably not, especially at this moment, with the=
 company wobbling on unsure financial footing. Until he turns around WBD, i=
f he can, and makes of it the success that many hoped he would when he merg=
ed Discovery with WarnerMedia in April 2022, it looks sketchy. But I give h=
im credit for at least making the argument and standing up for O.G. Hollywo=
od.

Zaslav has been obsessively cutting costs and paying down debt, from $55 bi=
llion down to $39+ billion. So the reduction in carriage fees and ads from =
Turner networks without the NBA must be really bad if he=E2=80=99s going to=
 sue over the $1.8 billion that
he could have saved in annual content costs, right? What do the numbers say=
?

Bill: We all know Zaz gets rewarded for paying down debt, and he=E2=80=99s =
done a pretty damn good job in the last two years, and what=E2=80=99s left =
has long-dated maturity and low cost. As I=E2=80=99ve written many times, W=
BD is a publicly traded leverage buyout, and like every other L.B.O., the e=
quity value won=E2=80=99t spring to life until that debt is paid down. Fort=
unately, Zaz has something like $6 billion in annual free cash flow that he=
 can use to pay down debt and to move WBD off the BBB cliff. If the credit =
agencies upgrade the WBD debt, I think that will be the moment when the mar=
ket rewards him and the WBD stock starts moving upward, on a path back and =
beyond where it was right after the merger in April 2022. (This is not inve=
stment advice.)

You=E2=80=99re a lot more optimistic than I am, considering the adjusted EB=
ITDA that this entire transaction was based on has been
consistently revised down. Just today, Morgan Stanley analyst Ben Swinburne=
 lowered his projection of EBITDA for this year to $9.5 billion from $9.7 b=
illion. Zaslav was talking about $14 billion a couple years ago, right?

Bill: Okay, Matt, that=E2=80=99s true and no one hates =E2=80=9Cadjusted EB=
ITDA=E2=80=9D more than I do, and missing =E2=80=9Cadjusted EBITDA=E2=80=9D=
 projections is even worse. So, as Zaz likes to say, he=E2=80=99s in the mi=
ddle of the lake and struggling for breath. He could either drown, or reach=
 out for lifelines as fast as he can. He reached out to Bob and Lachlan to =
create Venu and has teamed up with Bob on the Max, Disney+, Hulu bundle. Bu=
t I agree that unless he ditches the =E2=80=9Cadjusted EBITDA=E2=80=9D crut=
ch and starts hitting those projections, he will be in a bigger mess than h=
e already finds himself.

In the meantime, every little thing Zaz does gets scrutinized and criticize=
d, perhaps justly, from the H=C3=B4tel de Crillon stay at the Paris
Olympics to the mishandling of the NBA talks. My friends on Wall Street thi=
nk Zaz is barking up the wrong tree with the NBA lawsuit, and that it=E2=80=
=99s just an attempt to save face after blowing the negotiation. On the oth=
er hand, Matt, if WBD doesn=E2=80=99t have the NBA, that frees up something=
 like $25 billion for him to use elsewhere=E2=80=94making movies, paying ta=
lent, reducing debt. There=E2=80=99s no question that Zaz=E2=80=94like Iger=
, like Roberts, like the Murdochs, like Shari Redstone (for the next year o=
r so until the Ellison/RedBird deal closes)=E2=80=94wakes up each morning w=
ith huge problems. On the other hand, they all have a lot of great opportun=
ities in a business that people still really care about.

