dow end <i>without</i> getting a deal, and then was caught by surprise when=
 NBC came in with such a big bid. But his <i>biggest</i> mistake was not fo=
stering a better relationship with league officials. <br/><br/>One of WBD=
=E2=80=99s biggest selling points was that TNT has carried NBA games since =
the 1980s, but <i>none </i>of WBD=E2=80=99s top executives had deep relatio=
nships with the league. Zaslav took over WBD just two years ago and hired <=
b>Luis Silberwasser </b>shortly after. The Turner executives who negotiated=
 the previous NBA deal=E2=80=94<b>David Levy</b>, <b>Lenny Daniels</b>=E2=
=80=94were gone. Hollywood is a business of relationships, and sports media=
 is even <i>more</i> clubby. Sure, the
biggest check wins most of the time. But relationships really matter, and l=
eagues want to have confidence that they can work with media partners. <br/=
><br/><b>The Edelman story went around so fast that the NBA or Amazon must =
have leaked it. Which was totally predictable and why companies don=E2=80=
=99t hire big P.R. firms in these kinds of situations! Whose call was that?=
</b><br/><br/><i>John</i>: In all the years I=E2=80=99ve covered this space=
, I don=E2=80=99t think I=E2=80=99ve ever seen <b>Jesse Jackson</b> or NAAC=
P C.E.O. <b>Derrick Johnson</b> quoted as part of a P.R. campaign. Every pa=
rt of this push felt like it came straight out of Washington, and, coincide=
ntally enough, former <b>Obama</b> press secretary <b>Robert Gibbs </b>just=
 started as WBD=E2=80=99s communications chief. I know Gibbs says he had no=
thing to do with this campaign, but I can tell you that <i>every single one=
 </i>of my sources at the networks and the leagues believe that the Edelman=
 push came from him. <br/><br/><b>Dylan, you
<u><a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2U=
ktxclJLZ0dSQVljVWI4TFZOd0F0MmRWb1dpMD0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly9wdWNrLm5ld3Mv=
